The Mist ... Pondered<br>
-------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Selilya sat up with a start. It was dark save for the last glowing embers in the fireplace. The cold sweat seem to chill her body despite the bearskin coverings on the bed .... and .... him ....<br>
<br>
She smiled and bent over to kiss her new husband. His heavy, regular breaths indicated a most peaceful sleep. It had been a long, grueling day, first gathering everything for the Bonding Ceremony, arrival of guests, arranging the drink and food, the nerve-wracking march down the fallen log towards her betrothed, Ernseax, and the waiting Prophet and Priest Nospiratus, the realization that she was being taken against her will, the swirling mists enveloping her, the blackness, then a revival, then the vows and cheers and merriment...followed by the seemingly long trip to Selilya's cottage. He tended to her wounds...the bump on her head she suffered as she lost consciousness when the poison overcame her, the ragged cut on her left arm that had mysteriously appeared during the forced teleportation <br>
from the wedding site to the bowels of her captors' lair, and the raw scrape on her calf that could only have been the results of falling over some loose stones near the jail cells in Najena. For such a brash, rough warrior, he had been so very tender....<br>
<br>
Selilya slipped out from under the covers and made her way to her table, grabbing a tiny piece of kindling from the fireplace to light the lantern. The light illuminated her nude body and she paused as she saw her reflection in the looking glass. She could see the bandage on her arm that Ernseax had so carefully wrapped. It still throbbed. She leaned forward and touched her swollen temple... <br>
<br>
&quot;It is good to be alive,&quot; she whispered to herself. &quot;It was very close, though, very close.&quot; She reached over to her sitting chair, picking up her favorite robe, and pulled<br>
it around herself.<br>
<br>
&quot;The questions....Who was behind this? What does he want? Why? They are just too many,&quot; she mused. &quot;Indeed, this is like peering through the mist. I just know this, I cannot let them hurt those I care about. I must...make provision...&quot;<br>
<br>
She walked over to the wooden crate by the bed and lifted out several of the ancient scrolls she had been studying. The works of Miragul fascinated Selilya, especially the memoirs concerning his experiments...the ones right before the end...before he was driven away from everything...even life itself.<br>
<br>
&quot;He was so close...I know he was,&quot; she told herself. &quot;Life eternal was within his reach... The answer is here...it's here somewhere. What did he miss? I must find out. The experiments...these experiments...&quot;<br>
<br>
She closed her eyes briefly to relieve the pressure that seemed to explode in her forehead. She sat still for minutes until she no longer felt dizzy.<br>
<br>
&quot;Now that I have the help of the medical arts...perhaps it is time to acquire the first....uh....specimen. The first component...sheer strength he wrote,&quot; she was quietly muttering to herself. She gazed off into the night....<br>
<br>
&quot;McMad.&quot;<br>
<br>
She quietly laughed. She heard Ernseax cough and turned her head to look at him. The feelings of love and desire quickly overtook her thoughts of eternal life....<br>
<br>
She leaned over to the lantern and extinguished that flame. The robe dropped to the floor and she slipped back under the bed covers once again. <br>
<br>
